Welcome to notebook two — random variables and distributions. The English word variable is misleading. A random variable is not a variable. It is a function. Specifically, a function from the sample space omega to the real numbers.

For a coin flip, the indicator random variable x of heads equals one, x of tails equals zero. It turns the abstract outcome into a number we can do arithmetic on. For two rolls of a die, the random variable x equal to first roll plus second roll takes values from two to twelve. Both inputs are abstract outcomes. The random variable extracts a numeric summary.

Why bother? Because once outcomes are numbers, we can compute averages, variances, and run them through more functions. Every probabilistic model in machine learning is built on random variables — features x, labels y, parameters theta, hidden states z, all of them.

A convention. Uppercase letters for random variables. Lowercase for specific values the random variable might take. So p of capital x equals little x reads — the probability that the random variable x takes the value little x.

There are two flavors of random variables. A random variable is discrete if it can only take values in a finite or countable set — like zero one, or one through infinity, or words in a vocabulary. It is continuous if it ranges over an interval of the real line. These two flavors need slightly different machinery, but the ideas line up.

Now to p m f, p d f, and c d f — the three functions that describe a distribution.

A random variable does not really exist in isolation. It has a distribution, which is a description of how its values are spread. Three functions describe a distribution, depending on flavor.

The probability mass function, p m f, is for discrete x. The p m f is p sub x of x, equal to the probability that x equals little x. P m f values are actual probabilities. They sum to one over all x. For a fair die, the p m f equals one sixth for k equal to one through six.

The probability density function, p d f, is for continuous x. The p d f f sub x of x is not a probability. The probability that x equals any specific value is zero, because a continuous variable has infinitely many possible values. Instead the p d f describes probability per unit interval. The probability that x lies in an interval from a to b equals the integral, from a to b, of f sub x of x, d x.

The p d f integrates to one over its support. It can be greater than one at any point. It is a density, not a probability. The familiar bell curve — one divided by the square root of two pi, times e to the negative x squared over two — is the standard normal p d f. It peaks at about zero point four, not one.

The cumulative distribution function, c d f, works for both discrete and continuous random variables. The c d f is capital f sub x of x, equal to the probability that x is less than or equal to little x. The c d f starts at zero, monotonically increases to one, and ties together the discrete and continuous cases. Useful for sampling, for tail probabilities, and for testing.

Relationships. For continuous x, the c d f is the integral from negative infinity to x of the p d f. And by the fundamental theorem of calculus from the calculus repo, the p d f equals the derivative of the c d f. For discrete x, the c d f is the sum of p m f values up to x. The c d f jumps at each value where the p m f is positive.

The support is the set of values where the p m f or p d f is positive. The gaussian's support is the entire real line. The exponential's support is zero to infinity. The bernoulli's support is just zero and one.

Now let us go through the distributions you will use most. We start with bernoulli and binomial.

Bernoulli of p is the simplest distribution. X takes value one with probability p, and zero with probability one minus p. The p m f, written compactly, is p to the x, times one minus p to the one minus x — a slick way to write "p if x is one, one minus p if x is zero" in one formula.

Binomial of n and p counts the number of successes in n independent bernoulli trials, each with success probability p. The p m f is n choose k, times p to the k, times one minus p to the n minus k, for k from zero to n. The binomial coefficient n choose k counts the number of ways to arrange k successes among n trials.

A common confusion. Bernoulli is the single trial version. Binomial is the count over n trials version. Setting n equal to one recovers bernoulli.

Machine learning usage. Binary classification labels are bernoulli. Logistic regression is maximum likelihood estimation for a bernoulli likelihood — that is why its loss is the negative log of p of y given x. The cross entropy loss for binary classification — negative y times log p hat, minus one minus y, times log of one minus p hat — is literally the negative log of the bernoulli p m f, written with p hat as the predicted parameter.

Now categorical and multinomial. Categorical of p vector generalizes bernoulli to k outcomes. X takes value k from one to capital k, with probability p sub k. Where p is a probability vector — entries non negative, summing to one. The p m f is p sub x of k equals p sub k.

In code, categorical values are usually represented as one hot vectors — a vector with a single one in the k-th slot and zeros elsewhere. This is what softmax outputs are intended to model.

Multinomial of n and p vector counts how many times each of the k outcomes appears in n independent categorical draws. Y is a vector with components y sub k, summing to n. The p m f has a multinomial coefficient — n factorial divided by the product of n sub k factorial — multiplied by the product of p sub k to the n sub k.

Machine learning usage. Multi class classification — the predicted distribution over k classes is exactly a categorical with predicted p hat. Cross entropy loss against a one hot target is the negative log likelihood of the categorical. Language modeling — each next token distribution is a categorical over the vocabulary.

Now poisson and geometric. Poisson of lambda counts the number of events in a fixed time window, when events happen independently at average rate lambda. Support is zero, one, two, and so on. P m f is lambda to the k, times e to the negative lambda, divided by k factorial. Mean and variance both equal lambda.

The poisson is the "events are rare but many opportunities" limit of the binomial. As n goes to infinity, p goes to zero, and n times p approaches lambda, the binomial converges to a poisson.

Machine learning usage for poisson. Count data — word counts, click through events, fraud signals — are modeled as poisson. Poisson regression generalizes linear regression to count targets. Some attention variants use poisson processes for sparse attention patterns.

Geometric of p counts the number of trials until the first success in a sequence of bernoulli trials. Support starts at one. P m f is one minus p to the k minus one, times p. Mean is one over p. It is the discrete analogue of the exponential distribution, which it converges to in the small time step limit.

Machine learning usage for geometric. Modeling time to failure for systems. Reinforcement learning with discount factor gamma — a geometric distribution implicitly. Early stopping analysis.

Now the continuous staples — uniform, exponential, gaussian, beta, and gamma.

Uniform on a to b. Constant density on the interval, zero outside. The p d f equals one over b minus a, on the interval, and zero outside. Mean is a plus b over two. Variance is b minus a squared, divided by twelve. The flat distribution — your "I have no idea where it is in this range" prior.

Exponential of lambda. Models waiting time between independent events arriving at rate lambda. Support is zero to infinity. The p d f equals lambda, times e to the negative lambda x. Mean is one over lambda. Variance is one over lambda squared. The exponential is memoryless — having already waited t time units does not change the distribution of remaining wait. We will show this in the next notebook.

Gaussian, also called normal, of mu and sigma squared. The bell curve. The p d f is one over sigma, times the square root of two pi, all multiplied by the exponential of negative x minus mu, squared, divided by two sigma squared. Mean is mu. Variance is sigma squared. The single most important distribution in machine learning. Notebook five is dedicated to it.

Beta of alpha and beta. Support is the interval from zero to one. P d f is proportional to x to the alpha minus one, times one minus x to the beta minus one. The natural distribution over probabilities. Flexible shape controlled by alpha and beta. Conjugate to the bernoulli. We will use it in notebook six.

Gamma of alpha and beta. Support is zero to infinity. P d f is proportional to x to the alpha minus one, times e to the negative beta x. Generalizes the exponential at alpha equal to one. Models positive valued quantities. Conjugate to the poisson rate parameter.

Finally, the exponential family — the meta pattern most ML distributions belong to. Most of the distributions above — bernoulli, binomial, poisson, gaussian, beta, gamma, exponential, categorical, dirichlet — share a common shape. P of x given eta, a vector of natural parameters, equals h of x, times the exponential of eta transpose, times t of x, minus the log partition function a of eta.

The pieces. Eta is the natural parameters. T of x is the sufficient statistics. H of x is the base measure. And capital a of eta is the log partition function, which makes the density normalize.

This is called the exponential family, and it is where probability gets really beautiful. Key properties.

The sufficient statistic t of x summarizes the data perfectly. No information is lost by replacing x one through x n with the sum of t of x sub i.

Each exponential family distribution has a conjugate prior that is also exponential family. We will see beta bernoulli and gaussian gaussian conjugacy in notebook six.

The gradient of the log partition equals the expected sufficient statistic. This identity is the secret sauce of variational inference.

Maximum likelihood is easy — the gradient of the log likelihood involves only the empirical sufficient statistics.

In practice you do not need to chant the exponential family form every time. But knowing the framework explains why so many distributions feel related. They really are.

Generalized linear models, abbreviated g l m's, are the bridge to machine learning. Linear regression uses gaussian. Logistic regression uses bernoulli. Poisson regression uses poisson. Softmax regression uses categorical. All of them are g l m's, with different exponential family choices. The link functions are inverses of the canonical parameter mappings.

Let us close with where distributions appear in machine learning. They are the building blocks of probabilistic m l. Most architectures correspond to a choice of distribution for outputs and sometimes for latents.

Logistic regression and binary cross entropy. The output is bernoulli with p hat. The loss is the negative log of p of y given x.

Softmax classification and cross entropy. The output is categorical with p hat. The loss is again negative log likelihood.

Regression with m s e. The output is gaussian with mean y hat and variance sigma squared. The m s e loss is the negative log likelihood, up to constants.

Poisson regression for counts. Use a poisson output distribution with log lambda equal to w transpose, times x.

Variational auto encoders. Encoder outputs a gaussian over the latent. Decoder outputs bernoulli for images, or gaussian for continuous data.

Diffusion models. Each denoising step is a — usually gaussian — conditional distribution over the slightly less noisy version.

Language models. Each next token distribution is categorical over the vocabulary. The temperature in sampling literally rescales the natural parameters.

Latent dirichlet allocation, l d a. Documents are mixtures of topics drawn from dirichlets. Words are drawn from categoricals.

Gaussian processes. The output at every input is jointly gaussian. Leans on the multivariate gaussian for everything.

Mixture models, like gaussian mixture models. Probabilistic clustering with weighted sums of distributions, usually gaussian.

Bayesian neural networks. Treat weights as random variables. Specify priors, often gaussian. Compute approximate posteriors.

Reinforcement learning. Policies are distributions over actions. Rewards have distributions. Value functions are expectations.

The next notebook covers expectation, variance, and moments. How we summarize distributions with a few key numbers. And the identities — linearity, the law of the unconscious statistician, covariance — that you will lean on for the rest of the repo.
